race -- tSHORT FICTION AND POETRY -- tFunny Bones Are Good Bones: Atwood and Humour -- t"Back from the Dead": Journeys to the Underworld in Wilderness Tips -- t"It's still you": Aging and Identity in Atwood's Poetry -- t"Com [ing] Through Darkness": Margaret Atwood's 'T'-Opening Lyricism -- tPower Politics/ Power Politics: Atwood and Foucault -- tThe Two-Headed Opus -- tIncandescence: "the power of what is not there" in Margaret Atwood's Morning in the Burned House -- tEye-Openers: Photography in Margaret AtwoocTs Poetry -- tTHE BLIND ASSASSIN AND ORYX AND CRAKE -- tPower Politics/Power Politics: Atwood and Foucault -- tThe Body of/as Evidence: Margaret Atwood, The Blind Assassin and the Feminist Literary Mystery -- tThe Dead Are in the Hands of the Living: Memory Haunting Storytelling in Margaret Atwood's The Blind Assassin -- tMargaret Atwood and the Critical Limits of Embodiment -- tFrankenstein's Gaze and AtwoocTs Sexual Politics in Oryx and Crake -- tThe Representation of the Absent Mother in Margaret AtwoocPs Oryx and Crake -- tResistance in Futility: The Cyborg Identities of Oryx and Crake -- tOryx and Crake: Atwood's Ironic Inversion of Frankenstein -- tAtwoocTs Global Ethic: The Open Eye, The Blinded Eye -- tPOSTSCRIPT -- tPropositions from a (Reap)praising Margaret Atwood Conference -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMargaret Atwood enjoys a unique prominence in Canadian letters. With over thirty books to her credit, in genres ranging from children's writing to dystopic novels, she is as creatively diverse as she is internationally acclaimed. Her success, however, has been double-edged: the very popularity that makes her such a prominent figure in the literary world also renders her vulnerable to claims of being a "sell-out," as she relates in her Empson lectures. The Open Eye negotiates the space between these positions, acknowledging Atwood's remarkable achievement while considering how it impacts on national politics and identity.The range of perspectives in this volume is stimulating and enlightening. The Open Eye begins with a focus on Atwood as she presents herself and is presented in Canada and abroad, and then proceeds to consider, more broadly, the intersection of life and literature that Atwood's works and persona effect. It offers fresh insight into Atwood's early writing, redresses the critical void regarding her poetry and shorter prose pieces, and provides a critical base from which readers can assess Atwood's most recent novels.A common thread throughout these essays is the recognition of Atwood's importance in the literary realm in general, and in Canadian literature more particularly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBreitbach, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromberg, Pamela S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrydon, Dianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Wanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChivers, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavey, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDjwa, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdmonds, Regina M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvain, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiamengo, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoy, Nathalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodin, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct